title: Chocolate Muffins or Cupcakes
text: Chocolate muffins and cupcakes are basically the same, aren’t they? Except cupcakes have added frosting? This has been my most repeated recipes since it’s so easy and satisfies my chocolate cravings! With 1/4 cup honey, the bitterness is comparable to 90% dark chocolate to me, so I recommend you double the sugar if you prefer sweeter. This recipe makes 12 cupcakes.

title: Chocolate Muffins or Cupcakes
text:
Ingredients

Dry Ingredients

1 cup all-purpose flour
1/2 cup cocoa or cacao powder (cacao is the healthier option)
1 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp baking soda
1/2 tsp salt



Wet Ingredients

1/2 cup milk
1/4-1/2 cup honey or maple syrup
1/4 cup olive oil
1 large egg
1/2 tsp vanilla



Water

1/2 cup boiling bold expresso water

title: Chocolate Muffins or Cupcakes
text:
Instructions

Preheat oven to 325º F.
Add dry ingredients in a large bowl and whisk to combine well.
Add wet ingredients (excluding expresso) in another bowl and mix to combine well.
Combine the dry and wet ingredients and mix well on medium speed.
Reduce speed and add in boiling water.
Beat on high speed for about 1 minute to add air into the batter.
Fill cupcake liner about 1/2 full.
Bake until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean about 20 min.

title: Chocolate Muffins or Cupcakes
text:
Frosting
Combine the following and pipe or spread onto cupcakes.

1 large ripe avocado
1 tbsp coconut oil
1/3 cup cocoa or cacao powder
2-4 tbsp honey or maple syrup
1 tbsp milk

title: Sea Salt Vanilla Custard Ice Cream
text: Most ice creams, especially vanilla, are flavored with “natural flavors” which are not natural at all! It is nearly the same as artificial flavors, the only regulation being that it must be derived from any natural source. However, they may contain more than 100 different chemicals, including preservatives, solvents and other substances and still be called “natural flavors”. Not to mention all the added preservatives, gums, emulsifiers, and colorings in ice creams to increase the visual appeal, texture, and shelf life. I use vanilla extract in this recipe because vanilla beans are so expensive :( but if you have the means to use vanilla, I think it would work elegantly. You can also do a different flavoring or add in, ice cream is fun and flexible! Personally, my favorite combination is topping it off with olive oil and more salt. With these ingredients, I would even argue that ice cream can be a health food since full fat dairy products contain so many vitamins and minerals; honey is anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and antibacterial; and eggs are arguably the most nutrient dense food ;)

title: Sea Salt Vanilla Custard Ice Cream
text:
Ingredients

1 1/2 cups heavy cream
1 1/2 cups whole milk
1/4-1/2 tsp salt
4 large egg yolks
1/4-1/2 cup honey
1 1/2 tsp vanilla extract

title: Sea Salt Vanilla Custard Ice Cream
text:
Instructions

Heat the cream, milk, and salt on medium heat, stirring occasionally, until barely starting to simmer.
Whisk the egg yolks together in a bowl.
Temper the egg yolks by slowly adding a little bit of the hot cream mixture, whisking it in to prevent clumps.
Add in the egg yolk mixture to the pot, whisking the mixture together as you pour.
Cook over medium-low heat, stirring frequently, until slightly thickened.
Remove from the stove and whisk in honey and vanilla extract.
Cover and chill for at least 6 hours or overnight before churning in an ice cream maker.
